G.O.P. Operatives Get a Blue Wave Warning

While most of Capitol Hill was fixated on the South Carolina primary last n=
ight (Nancy Mace and William Timmons both fended off well-funded challenger=
s), another strange political story was developing in eastern Ohio=E2=80=94=
and dominating text chains across the Hill. In the special election race to=
 replace Bill Johnson, who resigned earlier this year, Republican candidate=
 Michael Rulli, who beat out Democrat Michael Kripchak, vastly underperform=
ed the district=E2=80=99s traditional partisan breakdown. Here=E2=80=99s wh=
y it=E2=80=99s causing a stir=E2=80=A6

* G.O.P. teeth-grinding: A year and a half ago, Johnson carried the distric=
t by a resounding 35 points. Last night, Rulli
edged out a nine-point victory. This was unnerving for some Republicans bec=
ause Rulli ran a traditional Republican campaign=E2=80=94complete with poll=
ing, direct mail, TV buys, and opposition research, while raising $680,000 =
and even putting $30,000 of his own money into the race (much of which went=
 toward the March Republican primary). But the real problem was that his op=
ponent, Kripchak, ran an eminently rudimentary=E2=80=94and threadbare=E2=80=
=94 campaign. His largest disbursement was $2,337=E2=80=94on yard signs.
* Incumbent warning signs: Democrats were obviously encouraged by the resul=
ts, while some Republican operatives muttered to me that this should be a w=
arning to some complacent incumbents. (In a midterm year, this would have b=
een a holy-shit, a-blue-wave-is-coming moment.) This seat is unlikely to be=
 competitive in the fall, but there are considerations regarding the larger=
 House battlefield. For now, the results seem to indicate that Democratic e=
nthusiasm in
low-turnout elections=E2=80=94dating back to the Dobbs decision=E2=80=94con=
tinues. But Trump=E2=80=99s coattails in the fall could just as easily offs=
et any potential Dobbs momentum in some places, which is why so many House =
and Senate races are so unpredictable. Meanwhile, other Republicans are arg=
uing that it was a safe seat, the Republican was always going to win, and t=
he low turnout discounts grand conclusions.

The indisputable short-term winner of this race, however, is Mike Johnson. =
Once Rulli is sworn in, Johnson will have a 218-214 majority=E2=80=94some m=
uch-needed breathing room, and only one week after Vince Fong filled Kevin =
McCarthy=E2=80=99s long-vacant seat.

