6c60617da42abd12a ), following an apparently Buzbee-placed Times story, for=
 allegedly having tried to kill Post stories regarding his old role assisti=
ng Rupert Murdoch in the wake of the U.K. phone-hacking scandal. (Lewis den=
ied having pressured Buzbee, and has denied any wrongdoing in the phone hac=
king affair). Another story, from NPR=E2=80=99s David Folkenflik, asserted =
that Lewis had offered him an exclusive interview if he dropped a story abo=
ut the Murdoch saga. The Post newsroom, already anxious and quietly seethin=
g about his recent comments that he couldn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Csugarcoat=E2=
=80=9D the company=E2=80=99s deficiencies, quickly aligned against him. The=
y had already circled the wagons on behalf of Buzbee, a mostly
unremarkable editor
who had been refashioned as a martyr.

Then Lewis went and made matters worse by being a little too characteristic=
ally frank with his feelings about the Post=E2=80=99s performance and the m=
otives of his accusers. He could hardly conceal his resentment in his glib =
responses to Post reporters for a piece last Thursday. On Friday, recognizi=
ng that his Fleet Street candor had violated the etiquette and traditions o=
f institutional Washington journalism, he apologized and committed himself =
to a listening tour=E2=80=94an attempted reset, or in Post corporate pablum=
, a chance to fix it.

In any event, Auletta seemed keen to turn the screws, perhaps in part becau=
se Buzbee is a fellow Livingston judge. In his opening speech, he called at=
tention to a recent report in Alan Rusbridger=E2=80=99s Prospect highlighti=
ng the allegation that Lewis knew of, or was involved in, News Corp.=E2=80=
=99s decision to delete 30 million emails and discard nine
boxes of potential evidence relating to the scandal. (In his prepared remar=
ks, Auletta wrote that Murdoch did this to =E2=80=9Ccover his ass=E2=80=9D;=
 alas, that pithy locution didn=E2=80=99t make it into the actual speech). =
He then called attention to Lewis=E2=80=99s alleged pressure campaigns agai=
nst Buzbee and Folkenflik, stating, =E2=80=9CLewis doesn=E2=80=99t get a pa=
ss.=E2=80=9D (History rhymes, of course: More than a decade ago, Auletta=E2=
=80=99s New Yorker column had been the vehicle for Jill Abramson=E2=80=99s =
version of the events surrounding her own ouster from the Times under its t=
hen-new British C.E.O., Mark Thompson.)

The tone and tenor of Auletta=E2=80=99s critique conveyed the challenges no=
w facing the Post=E2=80=99s publisher as he seeks to lead the paper out of =
its financial, editorial, and cultural morass. The man initially seen as th=
e Post=E2=80=99s potential savior has now become its latest scapegoat=E2=80=
=94which, as I noted last week, may limit his ability to enact the
strategic changes that are so obviously necessary. Indeed, a few beats late=
r in his speech, Auletta actually commended Lewis for pressing his newsroom=
 to =E2=80=9Crecognize=E2=80=9D the =E2=80=9Creality=E2=80=9D of its curren=
t financial woes. (Here again, the written draft was more apt: He commended=
 Lewis for injecting =E2=80=9Ca sense of alarm=E2=80=9D into the newsroom.)

After last week, however, Lewis must now pull this off with the handicap of=
 adhering to decorum and appeasing the Livingston set=E2=80=94those who, in=
 a fit of magical thinking, expect Jeff Bezos to either fire Lewis (he won=
=E2=80=99t, not for this anyway) or at least formalize the separation of ch=
urch and state between front office and newsroom. Alas, the tragedy here is=
 that church and state need to work more closely together to close the $77 =
million hole on the Post=E2=80=99s P&L. But that=E2=80=99s not conventional=
 wisdom in such circles. This week, former Post media columnist and New Yor=
k Times
public editor Margaret Sullivan called on Bezos to reinstate the role of th=
e ombudsman=E2=80=94epitomizing the misalignment between journalists=E2=80=
=99 concerns and the existential business problems that actually bedevil th=
e Post. This will not be the last such idea slipped into the public suggest=
ion box, of course.

Regardless, Lewis got the memo. In an internal meeting earlier this week, h=
e was described to me as being =E2=80=9Cmore contrite.=E2=80=9D In private =
conversations with staff, he is said to be choosing his words more carefull=
y. He is, it seems, being less direct. And he is leaving more of the day-to=
-day interfacing with the newsroom to his newly installed executive editor,=
 Matt Murray, a very affable guy and newsroom lifer whom reporters and edit=
ors seem to genuinely like and view as blameless for this shitshow. During =
these meetings, however, many staffers have expressed both concern over Mur=
ray=E2=80=99s successor, incoming editor Rob
Winnett, and Murray=E2=80=99s future gig=E2=80=94running the third newsroom=
=2E

We=E2=80=99ll see if Lewis=E2=80=99s contrition is effective, but the whole=
 penance tour raises a larger question. Inarguably, the challenges to exist=
ing business models call not for more decorum but for greater candor. Indee=
d, the urgency with which he had initially diagnosed the Post=E2=80=99s pro=
blems was actually his most refreshing characteristic. =E2=80=9CPeople are =
not reading your stuff=E2=80=9D may have offended some high priests in the =
newsroom, but it was also inarguably true. And perhaps the fact that it off=
ended some people says more about the Post=E2=80=99s culture than it does a=
bout Lewis, himself.

Anyway, one of the more depressing elements of this endlessly depressing in=
cident is that Lewis, who entered the company by calling for transparency (=
say it, fix it, etcetera), must now do what so many other media leaders hav=
e done in the past=E2=80=94pat his newsroom on
the collective head while doing the ugly business of making the numbers wor=
k behind the scenes. It=E2=80=99s a recipe for mutual distrust and contempt=
, and it=E2=80=99s not like that $77 million hole is going to be plugged by=
 a listening tour.

CNN Cuts

In a few weeks, I=E2=80=99m told, CNN C.E.O. Mark Thompson and his digital =
lieutenant, Alex MacCallum, will unveil to the staff their very long-awaite=
d plan to transform the beleaguered 44-year-old global newsroom into a dyna=
mic multiplatform business=E2=80=94one that will ostensibly deepen engageme=
nt among CNN=E2=80=99s large but transient online audience, introduce subsc=
ription offerings, and drive new revenue streams.

Needless to say, it can=E2=80=99t come soon enough. Last week, CNN averaged=
 just 485,000 viewers in primetime (roughly equivalent to the Food Network)=
 and 88,000 in the 25-to-54 demo (exactly equal to the Hallmark Channel). A=
nd while Thompson has long articulated the importance of prioritizing CNN=
=E2=80=99s post-linear future while giving his primetime anchors =E2=80=9Ct=
ime to bed in,=E2=80=9D he no doubt also recognizes that
linear continues to pay the bills=E2=80=94and, presumably, understands that=
 he needs to manage the decline of his television audience in order to buil=
d a runway for growth on streaming and digital.

To that end, Thompson earlier this week announced the news I had reported l=
ate last week: Charlie Moore, the longtime executive producer for Anderson =
Cooper=E2=80=99s 8 p.m show, will be elevated to vice president of primetim=
e programming, overseeing the hours between 7 p.m. and midnight. His move h=
as led to all manner of speculation in the newsroom: Is Anderson leaving CN=
N? (No, his contract runs to 2026.) Is he going to scale back to a Maddow-s=
tyle, once-a-week arrangement? (No, he doesn=E2=80=99t have that kind of fo=
llowing.) Is this a bad sign for Erin Burnett and her E.P. Susie Xu, who ha=
ve long competed with Anderson and Charlie for bookings and will now ostens=
ibly report to Charlie? (Yes, a little, but Erin=E2=80=99s show isn=E2=80=
=99t the problem, and
they=E2=80=99ll be fine).

In fact, the Moore promotion signals something far more simple but also mor=
e significant: a recognition on Thompson=E2=80=99s part that the primetime =
strategy he inherited=E2=80=94and, specifically, the post-Anderson hours fr=
om 9 p.m to midnight=E2=80=94actually does matter, and that it really isn=
=E2=80=99t working and needs to be fixed. And, furthermore, that programmin=
g chief Eric Sherling is too busy with the CNN Max strategy and the electio=
n and the upcoming presidential debate (the one night that will rate, bigly=
) to give those hours the attention they deserve. Whether that portends cha=
nges in the lineup or merely a renewed effort to produce the existing talen=
t is T.B.D.

Meanwhile, one thing I am certain about, unfortunately, is that there are m=
ore cuts coming at CNN. As part of Thompson=E2=80=99s grand transformation,=
 department leaders have been asked to submit names of staffers who might p=
otentially be cut, and
certain areas like digital editorial and international are expected to bear=
 an outsize share of the burden. It=E2=80=99s not clear exactly how many po=
sitions will be cut, and Thompson will likely make the cuts incrementally (=
and quietly) rather than all at once.

Asked about these impending cuts, a CNN spokesperson told me: =E2=80=9CAs M=
ark outlined this spring, we are undergoing a transformation to ensure CNN =
remains the global, multiplatform leader of news and information across tel=
evision, digital, and streaming platforms for generations to come. Hundreds=
 of people are involved in this process, and no final decisions have been m=
ade. Any reports to the contrary are inaccurate.=E2=80=9D

Thompson and MacCallum won=E2=80=99t be getting into this sort of nitty-gri=
tty, of course, as they present their vision. But these moves, uncomfortabl=
e as they may be, actually represent meaningful forward momentum. The Licht=
 era (or Licht-Zaz-Malone era) was defined by
screwing up stuff that had worked pretty well=E2=80=94moving Don Lemon to t=
he mornings, changing the chyrons, mashing up the morning, etcetera. Now, a=
fter quarters of studying the business, Thompson appears ready to really di=
g in and correct the mistakes.

