ominating text chains across the Hill. In the special election race to repl=
ace <b>Bill Johnson</b>, who resigned earlier this year, Republican candida=
te <b>Michael Rulli</b>, who beat out Democrat <b>Michael Kripchak</b>, <i>=
vastly</i> underperformed the district=E2=80=99s traditional partisan break=
down. Here=E2=80=99s why it=E2=80=99s causing a stir=E2=80=A6<br/><br/><ul =
style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:=
0;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>=
G.O.P. teeth-grinding</i>: A year and a half ago, Johnson carried the distr=
ict by a resounding 35 points. Last night, Rulli
edged out a nine-point victory. This was unnerving for some Republicans bec=
ause Rulli ran a traditional Republican campaign=E2=80=94complete with poll=
ing, direct mail, TV buys, and opposition research, while raising $680,000 =
and even putting $30,000 of his own money into the race (much of which went=
 toward the March Republican primary). But the real problem was that his op=
ponent, Kripchak, ran an eminently rudimentary=E2=80=94and threadbare=E2=80=
=94 campaign. His largest disbursement was $2,337=E2=80=94on <i>yard signs<=
/i>. </li><br/><li><i>Incumbent warning signs</i>: Democrats were obviously=
 encouraged by the results, while some Republican operatives muttered to me=
 that this should be a warning to some complacent incumbents. (In a midterm=
 year, this would have been a holy-shit, a-blue-wave-is-coming moment.) Thi=
s seat is unlikely to be competitive in the fall, but there are considerati=
ons regarding the larger House battlefield. For now, the results seem to in=
dicate that Democratic enthusiasm in
low-turnout elections=E2=80=94dating back to the <i>Dobbs </i>decision=E2=
=80=94continues. But Trump=E2=80=99s coattails in the fall could just as ea=
sily offset any potential <i>Dobbs</i> momentum in some places, which is wh=
y so many House and Senate races are so unpredictable. Meanwhile, other Rep=
ublicans are arguing that it was a safe seat, the Republican was <i>always<=
/i> going to win, and the low turnout discounts grand conclusions.<br/><br/=
>The indisputable short-term winner of this race, however, is <b>Mike Johns=
