          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">On Tuesday, about 1=
50 journalists gathered at The Yale Club in Midtown Manhattan for the annua=
l Livingston Awards, one of those <i>very</i> earnest midweek fork-clinking=
 ceremonies where journalists honor other journalists and, in this case, fu=
rnish winners with a $10,000 check from the University of Michigan=E2=80=99=
s Wallace House. <b>Remnick</b> and <b>Amanpour </b>each collected the awar=
d decades ago; more recent winners include <b>Ronan Farrow</b> and <b>Emily=
 Steel</b>. Each year, a veteran of the trade is also honored for his mento=
rship. This year, that honor went to former <i>L.A. Times</i> editor <b>Kev=
in Merida</b>.<br/><br/>As you can imagine, the programming at such events =
tends to be rather sincere and unremarkable, lest a speaker take the libert=
y of the lectern to touch a third rail or poke a bear. This year, a couple =
of the winners made a
few appeals to the Palestinian cause. But, for <i>this</i> crowd, the far m=
ore intriguing remarks came from <b>Ken Auletta</b>, the event=E2=80=99s ho=
st and veteran <i>New Yorker </i>media correspondent, and a Livingston judg=
e for more than four decades. Rather than issuing the usual paeans to the p=
rofession, Auletta dedicated much of his speech to criticizing <b>Will Lewi=
s</b>, the recently installed and <i>already </i>embattled publisher and C.=
E.O. of <i>The Washington Post</i>. <br/><br/>Last week, of course, Lewis v=
ery hastily and <i>inelegantly </i><u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/=
c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dRRHh2YzFXZE9Jd0hwWmRIbFE1OD0iL=
CJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvdGhlLXJlYWwtc3RvcnktYmVoaW5kLXNhbGx5LWJ1=
emJlZS1kZXBhcnR1cmUtZnJvbS13YXNoaW5ndG9uLXBvc3QvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrQmV=
zdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODYlMkYxMiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMD=
I2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslM=
jg2JTJGNiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291=
cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJ=
uYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo5MTM2MDh9/875f16611f882c8fb=
c641b79e14405ae918dcb40df7c8457e8f0bb28c188e54c" style=3D"color:#d40000;tex=
t-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">pushed out</a></u> execut=
ive editor <b>Sally Buzbee</b>=E2=80=94she resigned after refusing to accep=
t what was effectively a
demotion=E2=80=94and then <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWF=
pbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dRRHh2YzFXZE9Jd0hwWmRIbFE1OD0iLCJocmVmIj=
oiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvbGljZW5zZS10by13aWxsLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249VGhlK0Jlc=
3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg2JTJGMTIlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAy=
NnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI=
4NiUyRjYlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVyb=
mFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6OTE3NzAzfQ/5363ab90905fae8b8=
ede67324a0bac998a221f1269d2e40acd612aed9b6d6c6d" style=3D"color:#d40000;tex=
t-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">came under significant fi=
re</a></u>, following an apparently Buzbee-placed <i>Times </i>story, for a=
llegedly having tried to kill <i>Post </i>stories regarding his old role as=
sisting <b>Rupert Murdoch</b> in the wake of the U.K. phone-hacking scandal=
=2E (Lewis denied having pressured Buzb=
ee, and has denied any wrongdoing in t=
he phone hacking affair). Another story, from NPR=E2=80=99s <b>David Folken=
flik</b>, asserted that Lewis had offered him an exclusive interview if he =
dropped a story about the Murdoch saga. The <i>Post</i> newsroom, already a=
nxious and quietly seething about his recent comments that he couldn=E2=80=
=99t =E2=80=9Csugarcoat=E2=80=9D the company=E2=80=99s deficiencies, quickl=
y aligned against him. They had already circled the wagons on behalf of Buz=
bee, a mostly unremarkable editor
who had been refashioned as a martyr. <br/><br/>Then Lewis went and made ma=
tters worse by being a little <i>too</i> characteristically frank with his =
feelings about the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s performance and the motives of his=
 accusers. He could hardly conceal his resentment in his glib responses to =
<i>Post </i>reporters for a piece last Thursday. On Friday, recognizing tha=
t his Fleet Street candor had violated the etiquette and traditions of inst=
itutional Washington journalism, he apologized and committed himself to a l=
istening tour=E2=80=94an attempted reset, or in <i>Post </i>corporate pablu=
m, a chance to <i>fix it</i>.<br/><br/>In any event, Auletta seemed keen to=
 turn the screws, perhaps in part because Buzbee is a fellow Livingston jud=
ge. In his opening speech, he called attention to a recent report in <b>Ala=
n Rusbridger</b>=E2=80=99s <i>Prospect</i> highlighting the allegation that=
 Lewis knew of, or was involved in, News Corp.=E2=80=99s decision to delete=
 30 million emails and discard nine
boxes of potential evidence relating to the scandal. (In his prepared remar=
ks, Auletta wrote that Murdoch did this to =E2=80=9Ccover his ass=E2=80=9D;=
 alas, that pithy locution didn=E2=80=99t make it into the actual speech). =
He then called attention to Lewis=E2=80=99s alleged pressure campaigns agai=
nst Buzbee and Folkenflik, stating, =E2=80=9CLewis doesn=E2=80=99t get a pa=
ss.=E2=80=9D (History rhymes, of course: More than a decade ago, Auletta=E2=
=80=99s <i>New Yorker </i>column had been the vehicle for <b>Jill Abramson<=
/b>=E2=80=99s version of the events surrounding her own ouster from the <i>=
Times</i> under its then-new British C.E.O., <b>Mark Thompson</b>.) <br/><b=
r/>The tone and tenor of Auletta=E2=80=99s critique conveyed the challenges=
 now facing the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s publisher as he seeks to lead the pap=
er out of its financial, editorial, and cultural morass. The man initially =
seen as the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s potential savior has now become its lates=
t scapegoat=E2=80=94which, as I noted last week, may limit his ability to e=
nact the
strategic changes that are so <i>obviously</i> necessary. Indeed, a few bea=
ts later in his speech, Auletta actually <i>commended</i> Lewis for pressin=
g his newsroom to =E2=80=9Crecognize=E2=80=9D the =E2=80=9Creality=E2=80=9D=
 of its current financial woes. (Here again, the written draft was more apt=
: He commended Lewis for injecting =E2=80=9Ca sense of alarm=E2=80=9D into =
the newsroom.) <br/><br/>After last week, however, Lewis must now pull this=
 off with the handicap of adhering to decorum and appeasing the Livingston =
set=E2=80=94those who, in a fit of magical thinking, expect <b>Jeff Bezos <=
/b>to either fire Lewis (he won=E2=80=99t, not for <i>this </i>anyway) or a=
t least formalize the separation of church and state between front office a=
nd newsroom. Alas, the tragedy here is that church and state need to work <=
i>more closely</i> together to close the $77 million hole on the <i>Post</i=
>=E2=80=99s P&amp;L. But that=E2=80=99s not conventional wisdom in such cir=
cles. This week, former <i>Post </i>media columnist and <i>New York Times
</i>public editor <b>Margaret Sullivan</b> called on Bezos to reinstate the=
 role of the ombudsman=E2=80=94epitomizing the misalignment between journal=
ists=E2=80=99 concerns and the existential business problems that <i>actual=
ly</i> bedevil the <i>Post</i>. This will not be the last such idea slipped=
 into the public suggestion box, of course.<br/><br/>Regardless, Lewis got =
the memo. In an internal meeting earlier this week, he was described to me =
as being =E2=80=9Cmore contrite.=E2=80=9D In private conversations with sta=
ff, he is said to be choosing his words more carefully. He is, it seems, be=
ing <i>less </i>direct. And he is leaving more of the day-to-day interfacin=
g with the newsroom to his newly installed executive editor, <b>Matt Murray=
</b>, a very affable guy and newsroom lifer whom reporters and editors seem=
 to genuinely like and view as blameless for this shitshow. During these me=
etings, however, many staffers have expressed both concern over Murray=E2=
=80=99s successor, incoming editor <b>Rob
Winnett</b>, and Murray=E2=80=99s future gig=E2=80=94running the <i>third n=
ewsroom</i>.<br/><br/>We=E2=80=99ll see if Lewis=E2=80=99s contrition is ef=
fective, but the whole penance tour raises a larger question. Inarguably, t=
he challenges to existing business models call not for more decorum but for=
 <i>greater </i>candor. Indeed, the urgency with which he had initially dia=
gnosed the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s problems was actually his most refreshing =
characteristic. =E2=80=9CPeople are <i>not reading your stuff</i>=E2=80=9D =
may have offended some high priests in the newsroom, but it was also inargu=
ably true. And perhaps the fact that it offended some people says more abou=
t the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s culture than it does about Lewis, himself. <br/=
><br/>Anyway, one of the more depressing elements of this endlessly depress=
ing incident is that Lewis, who entered the company by calling for transpar=
ency (<i>say it</i>, <i>fix it</i>, etcetera), must now do what so many oth=
er media leaders have done in the past=E2=80=94pat his newsroom on
the collective head while doing the ugly business of making the numbers wor=
k behind the scenes. It=E2=80=99s a recipe for mutual distrust and contempt=
, and it=E2=80=99s not like that $77 million hole is going to be plugged by=
 a listening tour.<br/></td>
